# JSX String Safety

Never use unescaped apostrophes or quotes inside JSX string literals — they break the Babel/Vite parser.

## The Problem

```tsx
// ❌ BAD — the apostrophe in "it's" terminates the string early
{'We extracted this date. Please confirm it's correct.'}

// ❌ BAD — escaped with backslash still fails in JSX expression strings
{'We couldn\'t find a date.'}
```

## Solutions

```tsx
// ✅ Use Unicode curly apostrophe (\u2019)
{'Please confirm it\u2019s correct.'}

// ✅ Use HTML entity
{"Please confirm it&apos;s correct."}

// ✅ Use template literal (backticks don't conflict)
{`Please confirm it's correct.`}

// ✅ Use double-quoted string with apostrophe inside
{"We couldn't find a calendar date."}
```

**Preferred approach**: Use template literals (backticks) for any JSX string containing apostrophes, quotes, or other special characters.
